  "articleSummary": "The article argues that \"generative UI\" is not a single technology but a layered stack—product shell, UI composition model, runtime/transport, and agent/tool backend—and that conflating these layers leads to confusion. It introduces a control spectrum from tool-to-component rendering (safest default) to open-ended generated HTML, emphasizing the trade-off between developer control and agent freedom. Key technologies discussed include AG-UI, A2UI, json-render, CopilotKit, and OpenAI Apps SDK, each positioned within specific layers. The tone is analytical and explanatory, using metaphors like \"training wheels\" for chat, \"soup\" for blurred concepts, and \"command palette wearing a costume\" for over-controlled UI. The intended audience is developers and architects building LLM-powered applications with generative interfaces.",
